Data manipulations

Passenger Miles on Commercial US Airlines, 19371960

Description

The revenue passenger miles flown by commercial airlines in the United States for each year from 1937 to 1960.

Usage

airmiles

Task

  1. Create vector for miles from 1950 to 1955 (included) and calculate mean.

  2. Calculate sum of all odd years

  3. Summarise all miles per periods: 1937 - 1940, 1941-1950, 1951 - 1960

  4. Calculate difference between summarised miles per periods 1941-1950, 1951 - 1960

Monthly Airline Passenger Numbers 1949-1960

Description

The classic Box & Jenkins airline data. Monthly totals of international airline passengers, 1949 to 1960.

Usage

AirPassengers

Format

A monthly time series, in thousands.

Task

  1. Create vector for May passengers and calculate its mean

  2. What month gives the biggest sum of passengers? Define function to calculate sum for arbitrary month. Find the maximum sum.

  3. What year gives the biggest mean of passengers? Define function to calculate mean for arbitrary year. Find the maximum mean.

New York Air Quality Measurements

Description

Daily air quality measurements in New York, May to September 1973.

Usage

airquality

Format

A data frame with 154 observations on 6 variables.

Details

Daily readings of the following air quality values for May 1, 1973 (a Tuesday) to September 30, 1973.

Ozone: Mean ozone in parts per billion from 1300 to 1500 hours at Roosevelt Island

Solar.R: Solar radiation in Langleys in the frequency band 40007700 Angstroms from 0800 to 1200 hours at Central Park

Wind: Average wind speed in miles per hour at 0700 and 1000 hours at LaGuardia Airport

Temp: Maximum daily temperature in degrees Fahrenheit at La Guardia Airport.

Task

  1. Calculate number of observation without (any) missing values (NAs)

  2. Create function which returns temperature for all ns days of month (for example all temperatures for first days are 67, 78, 84, 81, 91)

  3. Create data frame with temperature and ozon variables summarized by month excluding NAs (Write code that creates such data frame)

  4. Calculate mean of Solar radiation varable for 5th month

  5. Create data frame with two columns: Ozone maximum values per month and monthes

  6. Calculate number of days when Wind was bigger then median value

  7. Calculate total number of observation with at least on NA value

  8. Create data frame with 10 observation with lowest temperature

  9. Convert airquality dataset to dataframe and add column - temperature in Celsius degrees, rounded to integer value

  10. Convert airquality dataset to dataframe and add column using Month and Day - date in format Year-Month-Day (year is in dataset description)

  11. Calculate number of observation where solar radiation was in 100 - 200 range and wind was less then 12.

The ChatterjeePrice Attitude Data

Description

From a survey of the clerical employees of a large financial organization, the data are aggregated from the questionnaires of the approximately 35 employees for each of 30 (randomly selected) departments. The numbers give the percent proportion of favourable responses to seven questions in each department.

Usage

attitude

Format

A data frame with 30 observations on 7 variables. The first column are the short names from the reference, the second one the variable names in the data frame

Task

  1. Create function which takes name of column as an argument and returns mean of values for this column

  2. Calculate mean of all columns exept rating. Is it equal to value of rating?

  3. Extract all observations where learning value is higher than privileges value and complaints value is bigger than 50.

  4. How many unique values exist for each column. Create function to calculate.

  5. Create data frame with persons who prefer privileges more than average (mean) level of privileges.

  6. Create data frame with observations which are in top 25% values for learning or advance values

Quarterly Time Series of the Number of Australian Residents

Description

Numbers (in thousands) of Australian residents measured quarterly from March 1971 to March 1994. The object is of class ts.

Usage

austres

Task

  1. Create data frame with two columns - date (year + quarter) and value (amount). Convert austres dataset into this data frame.

  2. Create vector of values for 1 quarter of each year and calculate sum.

  3. Calculate how many observations are in 1300 - 1500 range?

  4. Round values to integer numbers. Create vector with unique values.

  5. Create vector of sums per each 5 years and define data frame with two columns - first column - range of time (eg 1971-1975) and second - total number of residents.

  6. Create data frame with year and max value (max amoung quarters for this year) for it. Add new column - percent comparing to first (1971) year and calculate this percent for each year.

  7. Create data frame with year, max amd min value (max and min amoung quarters for this year) for it. Add new column - difference between max and min and calculate this value for each year.

  8. Create data frame with year and average value (average amoung quarters for this year) for it. Add new column - percent comparing previous year and calculate this value for each year.

Body Temperature Series of Two Beavers

Description

Reynolds (1994) describes a small part of a study of the long-term temperature dynamics of beaver Castor canadensis in north-central Wisconsin. Body temperature was measured by telemetry every 10 minutes for four females, but data from a one period of less than a day for each of two animals is used there.

Usage

beaver1 beaver2

Format

The beaver1 data frame has 114 rows and 4 columns on body temperature measurements at 10 minute intervals.

The beaver2 data frame has 100 rows and 4 columns on body temperature measurements at 10 minute intervals.

The variables are as follows:

day Day of observation (in days since the beginning of 1990), December 1213 (beaver1) and November 34 (beaver2).

time Time of observation, in the form 0330 for 3:30am

temp Measured body temperature in degrees Celsius.

activ Indicator of activity outside the retreat.

Note

The observation at 22:20 is missing in beaver1.

Task

  1. For beaver1, beaver2 dataset. Create function to transform day and time into time from the first observation (in minutes) and apply it to beavers datasets.

  2. For beaver1, beaver2 dataset. Calculate maximum temperature for active and passive state for each beaver and compare values.

  3. For beaver1, beaver2 dataset. Calculate average temperature for active and passive state for each beaver per day.

  4. For beaver1 dataset. Calculate average temperature per hour for each day. Find hour with the biggest difference.

  5. For beaver1, beaver2 dataset. Consider hypothesis: beaver temperature is always bigger when they active. Prove or discard this hypothesis (create R function to calculate number of observations when it fails).

  6. For beaver1, beaver2 dataset. Consider hypothesis: beaver temperature is in average bigger when they active. Prove or discard this hypothesis (create R function to calculate number of observations when it fails).

  7. For beaver2 dataset. Calculate average temp (for all observations) and create data frame with all observations which are bigger than average.

  8. For beaver1, beaver2 dataset. Calculate total amount of time (in minutes) of active state for each beaver.

  9. For beaver1, beaver2 dataset. Calculate ratio of activity for each beaver (time in active state/ total time).

  10. For beaver2. Create data frame with average temperature per hour. Calculate ratio to max column (current temperature/ max temperature)

  11. For beaver1. Create data frame with average temperature per hour. Calculate ratio to previous column (current temperature/ previous observation temperature)

  12. For beaver1, beaver2 dataset. Create data frame with columns - hour (from the 00:00), temperature of 1 beaver, temperature of 2 beaver, difference (temp1 - temp2).
